title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>We know <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Bbbk ^{\times }=\langle  a\rangle ]]></fr:tex> where <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in \Bbbk ]]></fr:tex> is of order <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p^{n}-1]]></fr:tex>. We can then write,
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}_{p^{n}}=\mathbb {F}_{p}(a);]]></fr:tex>
and if <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma \in \mathop {\textrm {Aut}}\nolimits (\Bbbk  / \mathbb {F})]]></fr:tex>, then it is determined by <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma (a)]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p>Observe the minimal polynomial of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> has degree <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\deg (m_{a})=n]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p>We claim <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\phi _{r}(a)]]></fr:tex> (for <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[r=0,…,n-1]]></fr:tex>) are the <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> distinct roots of this polynomial. Otherwise, if there is a <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[r<s]]></fr:tex> such that
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\phi _{r}(a)=\phi _{s}(a),]]></fr:tex>
then we would have
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[a^{p^{r}}=a^{p^{s}},]]></fr:tex>
which means
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[a^{p^{n-s+r}}=a^{p^{n}}=a,]]></fr:tex>
which contradicts <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a^{k}\neq 1]]></fr:tex> for <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[k<p^{n}-1]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
class="qed">∎</html:span></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
 

